For interactive prompts, use Bun's built-in prompt() or the readline module from node:readline. Bun supports readline/promises.

The simplest approach using node:readline/promises:
```typescript
import { createInterface } from 'node:readline/promises';
const rl = createInterface({ input: process.stdin, output: process.stdout });
const name = await rl.question('Plugin name (lowercase, hyphens ok): ');
const domain = await rl.question('Target domain (e.g., .slack.com): ');
```

In create-plugin/src/index.ts, modify the commander setup: make the <name> argument optional. If not provided (and --domain not provided), enter interactive mode.

For plugin.ts, do the same for the 'create' subcommand.

Edit platform/cli/src/scaffold.ts generateReadme function (around line 189-266). Add a new section after 'Adding Tools':

```markdown
## Shared Schemas

When multiple tools share the same input or output shapes, extract common Zod schemas into a shared file:

```ts
// src/schemas/channel.ts
import { z } from 'zod';

export const channelSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().describe('Channel ID'),
  name: z.string().describe('Channel name'),
});

export type Channel = z.infer<typeof channelSchema>;
```

Then import and reuse in tools:

```ts
import { channelSchema } from '../schemas/channel.js';

export const listChannels = defineTool({
  // ...
  output: z.object({ channels: z.array(channelSchema) }),
});
```
```
